        for (int i = 0; i < 2 * n; ++i) {
            std::cin >> a[i];
        }
        std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        // The problem asks to partition 2n students into two classes, each with an odd number of students.
        // Let the sizes of the classes be S1 and S2. S1 + S2 = 2n. S1 and S2 must be odd.
        // The median of a class of size 2k+1 is the (k+1)-th element in sorted order (1-indexed).
        // This means it's the element at index k (0-indexed).
        //
        // Consider the sorted array a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        //
        // If we pick the first n elements for one class and the last n elements for the other,
        // this would mean each class has size n.
        // If n is odd, then this is a valid partition.
        // The median of the first class (a_0, ..., a_{n-1}) would be a_{(n-1)/2}.
        // The median of the second class (a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}) would be a_{n + (n-1)/2}.
        // The difference would be |a_{n + (n-1)/2} - a_{(n-1)/2}|.
        //
        // However, the problem statement implies that we can choose any odd sizes S1, S2 such that S1+S2=2n.
        // The key insight is that to minimize the difference between medians, we should try to make the medians as close as possible.
        //
        // Let's consider the case where n is odd.
        // We can form two classes of size n.
        // The first class takes students a_0, ..., a_{n-1}. Its median is a_{(n-1)/2}.
        // The second class takes students a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}. Its median is a_{n + (n-1)/2}.
        // The difference is a_{n + (n-1)/2} - a_{(n-1)/2}.
        //
        // Let's consider the case where n is even.
        // We cannot form two classes of size n, because n is even.
        // The smallest odd size is 1. The largest odd size is 2n-1.
        //
        // The problem asks for the minimum possible absolute difference.
        //
        // The crucial observation is that if we sort all 2n skill levels,
        // the median of any class of size $2k+1$ will be one of the $a_i$ values.
        //
        // Consider the specific partition where the first class consists of the first $n$ students in the sorted list,
        // and the second class consists of the remaining $n$ students.
        // This means the first class has students $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$.
        // The second class has students $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        //
        // Each class has $n$ students.
        // If $n$ is odd, then this is a valid partition.
        // The median of the first class is $a_{(n-1)/2}$.
        // The median of the second class is $a_{n + (n-1)/2}$.
        // The difference is $a_{n + (n-1)/2} - a_{(n-1)/2}$.
        //
        // What if $n$ is even? Then this partition is not valid because classes must have an odd number of students.
        //
        // Let's re-evaluate the problem statement.
        // "each class has odd number of students"
        // "The number of students in the classes may be equal or different, by your choice."
        //
        // The problem is simpler than it seems.
        // The minimum possible absolute difference is always achieved by taking the median of the first $n$ elements and the median of the last $n$ elements.
        // This is because the problem asks for *any* partition.
        //
        // If we sort the entire array $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // We can always form two classes of size $n$ if $n$ is odd.
        // Class 1: $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$. Median $M_1 = a_{(n-1)/2}$.
        // Class 2: $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$. Median $M_2 = a_{n + (n-1)/2}$.
        // The difference is $M_2 - M_1$.
        //
